A team is building a payment processing system in .NET using Temporal. Their `ProcessPaymentActivity` calls an external payment gateway that occasionally returns HTTP 429 (rate limited) responses. They implement the following pattern:

```csharp
[Activity]
public async Task<PaymentResult> ProcessPaymentAsync(PaymentRequest request)
{
    var attempt = ActivityExecutionContext.Current.Info.Attempt;
    try
    {
        return await _gateway.SubmitPaymentAsync(request);
    }
    catch (RateLimitedException ex)
    {
        throw new ApplicationFailureException(
            "Rate limited by payment gateway",
            inner: ex,
            category: ApplicationErrorCategory.Benign,
            nextRetryDelay: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5 * attempt));
    }
}
```

The activity is scheduled with:
```csharp
new() {
    ScheduleToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2),
    StartToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30),
    RetryPolicy = new() {
        MaximumAttempts = 10,
        MaximumInterval = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(60)
    }
}
```

During a severe rate-limiting event, the gateway rate-limits the first 6 attempts. The team notices the activity fails permanently before exhausting all 10 attempts. Which combination of factors causes this premature failure?

